From 06c8204b3007aaf090e64e97b18cddd7736b2a42 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Matej Formanek <manekmatej@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 11 Jun 2026 13:09:01 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] hstore: validate structure before trusting HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION

contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c::hstoreUpgrade() returns the input
hstore unchanged when its HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION bit is set:

    if (hs->size_ & HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION)
        return hs;

The function hstoreValidNewFormat() in the same file short-circuited
the same way:

    if (hs->size_ & HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION)
        return 2;

Both checks trust the flag without inspecting the entry array.  A
forged datum can set HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION on top of garbage HEntry
offsets; downstream macros (HSE_ISFIRST, HSE_ENDPOS, HSTORE_KEY,
HSTORE_VAL) then memcpy off attacker-controlled offsets.  The
realistic forgery vector is a malicious bytea fed via dump / restore
or COPY ... FROM with an hstore column, producing a controllable
out-of-bounds read in the consuming session.

This commit closes both halves of the trust gap:

* hstoreValidNewFormat() always runs the structural pass; the flag is
  only an intent signal, not a trust signal.

* hstoreUpgrade() only short-circuits when both the flag AND the
  structural check agree.  Forged datums fall through to the existing
  dual-validation path (valid_new + valid_old), which already rejects
  inconsistent inputs.

Reported in postgres-claude corpus sweep A13 (2026-06-09); see
knowledge/issues/hstore.md.
---
 contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c | 24 ++++++++++++++++++++----
 1 file changed, 20 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

diff --git a/contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c b/contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c
index 3a9f7f45cb7..e4ab648512e 100644
--- a/contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c
+++ b/contrib/hstore/hstore_compat.c
@@ -127,8 +127,16 @@ hstoreValidNewFormat(HStore *hs)
 	int			vsize = CALCDATASIZE(count, buflen);
 	int			i;
 
-	if (hs->size_ & HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION)
-		return 2;
+	/*
+	 * Previously this short-circuited to "valid" whenever
+	 * HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION was set, trusting the flag without inspecting the
+	 * underlying entry array.  That left the downstream HSTORE_KEY /
+	 * HSTORE_VAL macros open to forged datums whose offset entries are
+	 * structurally invalid - a controllable out-of-bounds read via dump /
+	 * restore or COPY-supplied bytea.  Run the full structural validation
+	 * regardless of the flag; the flag only indicates that the producer
+	 * believed it was emitting the new format, not that the bytes obey it.
+	 */
 
 	if (count == 0)
 		return 2;
@@ -238,8 +246,16 @@ hstoreUpgrade(Datum orig)
 	int			valid_new;
 	int			valid_old;
 
-	/* Return immediately if no conversion needed */
-	if (hs->size_ & HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION)
+	/*
+	 * Return immediately if the new-version flag is set AND the structure
+	 * actually obeys the new format.  A forged datum can set the flag
+	 * with garbage offsets in the entry array, so the flag alone is not
+	 * a safe trust signal.  hstoreValidNewFormat() now inspects structure
+	 * unconditionally; only return early when both the flag and the
+	 * structure agree, otherwise fall through to the dual-validation
+	 * recovery path below.
+	 */
+	if ((hs->size_ & HS_FLAG_NEWVERSION) && hstoreValidNewFormat(hs))
 		return hs;
 
 	/* Do we have a writable copy? If not, make one. */
